ty and gullibility, flames may come my way.  Sobeit.<br>
<br>
Yesterday I was the victim of a scam.  I was auctioning to trade PP from FV to Morell Thule - a large sum of it.  A player named Dirfrops responded and a conversation ensued.  He informed me he had PP on Morell Thule and wished to do the trade.  Now, understand - I've done cross-server trades many times.  I did a cross-server trade to get PP on Firiona, and over the last few years, I've never had a problem - because I've learned the golden rule of *never trust anyone*.  Always trade in small increments.  Always be cautious.  Anyway, Dirfrops did something that other players in the past had not offered to do - he offered to call me on the phone and talk one-on-one to ensure confidence in the trade.  Immediately I agreed and he called.  He seemed nice enough - a teenager obviously (19 at the most), who obviously had some knowledge about EQ.  We spoke for 15 minutes or so when we finally started the trade.  During that time, I figured &quot;What the heck - the guy seems nice enough, honest enough, and he's on the phone with me.  So I'll go ahead and trade my PP to him lump sum.&quot;  And that's all she wrote.  The next thing I know - *click* the phone is hung up - and I no longer get replies when messaging Dirfrops.  It's immediately apparent to me that everything this person has told me over the phone - where they live, what they do, their name, the fact that they even had PP to trade on Morell - was a lie.  Of course I'm feeling amazingly angry and stupid all at the same time.  It's obvious that it was a scam.  <br>
<br>
I'm a 5 year EQ veteran, have come across all types, and generally error on the side of caution usually.  This time was the obvious exception.  My point is twofold.  I got taken because I had faith that a person's word MEANS SOMETHING.  It doesn't.  One would think that actually SPEAKING on the phone to a person, talking about life, work, etc would make a difference and would say something about their integrity.  Well it does say something about their integrity - it says they have none.  It says you cannot trust anyone, regardless of how well you think you know them online, how much you've spoken to them on the phone.  What it also says is how SAD it is that people have absolutely NO integrity or honesty within them whatsoever.  It's SAD that someone would lie to your face and take that which took you 3 years to earn and then go and sell it on PlayerAuctions or for some other use.  Frankly, I don't know how these people sleep at night.  I don't know how they can look themselves in the mirror each day and live with themselves.  They wouldn't know the meaning of the word &quot;character&quot; if it hit them across the face.  <br>
<br>
My lesson has been learned and I'll take my medicine like a good boy and go on just fine.  However, I have two things to say.  One - be careful.  Be careful of this person (Dirfrops) and any other characters he may be playing on seperate accounts.  Be careful of people in general.  The moral of this story is also not to do cross-server trades - not to trust people at all.  It's embarassing to myself and others.  I'm not the first - and I won't be the last.  <br>
<br>
Secondly - I have something to say to Dirfrops himself (assuming he reads this).  I want you to know that you got a big chunk of change and I'm sure you laughed all the way to the bank.  I want you to know that you haven't ruined my enjoyment of Everquest in any way.  Yes, it was disappointing, but I intend to log in today and enjoy myself despite spineless exploiters.  I want you to know that all you have done is take another piece of your soul and thrown it down the garbage disposal.  I hope it was worth it.  I hope that it was worth sacrificing your integrity for some pixels on the screen or for a few dollars you might get online.  I also want you to know that there are *always* consequences.  Bet on it.  You will be held accountable for what you've done.  No - it may not be by me, because I didn't get your RL information.  But rest assured - you will pay - and when you do, the &quot;EQ play money&quot; or the RL money you get for selling it, won't come close to being worth it.  It's sad.  It's sad that at the end of your days, your soul with be worth nothing.  Despite all this, I want you to know that I will pray for people like you.  I'll pray that despite your evil tendencies will catch up with you and that you'll see the error of your ways and make amends.  As gullible as I was this one time, I am still better off than you - a person without hope.  I pray you'll find it.  It's never too late.  <br>
<br>
Thanks for your time.<br>
<br>
